BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Demo] How to get data out of complex documents using AI
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T090000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T100000
UID:nicar-2026-1002@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Learn how newsrooms get important information out of large vol
 umes of documents (pdfs\, audio transcripts) and vet the results to power 
 reporting.\n\nAI\, Tools & Tech | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River D
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1002
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Everyone can be (and should be) a housing reporter
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T143000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T153000
UID:nicar-2026-1007@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:The housing crisis is touching communities of every size — n
 ot just coastal cities or low‑income renters. In this session\, we’ll 
 walk through practical data tools\, sources\, and reporting techniques to 
 cover affordable housing challenges\, evictions\, and homelessness. Whethe
 r you’re new to the beat\, jumping on a fast-moving daily story\, or loo
 king to deepen your expertise\, you’ll learn accessible methods for find
 ing\, analyzing\, and localizing housing data to produce clearer\, more im
 pactful reporting.\n\nBeat reporting | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River G
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1007
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] AI concepts you should know
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T143000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T153000
UID:nicar-2026-1008@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:AI\, Machine Learning\, Deep Learning ... what do these terms 
 really mean\, and what is the difference? Many journalists are still grapp
 ling with an explosion of buzzwords and concepts. This session aims to dem
 ystify the jargon and provide a clear\, practical explanation of key AI te
 rms and tools.\n\nAI | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River D
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1008
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] From delving into data to door knocking: Finding people be
 hind the numbers and getting them to speak
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T101500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T111500
UID:nicar-2026-1009@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:You've finished your FOIAs. You've done the data analysis. You
 've talked with experts. Now you're ready to put your story together. Ther
 e's just one problem. You haven't yet spoken to the people who are impacte
 d by the findings found in your research. In this panel\, journalists from
  across the media landscape talk about ways they've found people who are i
 mpacted by the topics they were covering and/or data they were researching
 . Plus\, once you've found the people\, how do you convince them to go on 
 the record? The panelists are here to answer your questions and talk about
  how they centered their stories around the people they found.\n\nStory id
 eas | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River D
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1009
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Collaborating in an intergenerational workspace: let's get
  to yes
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T143000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T153000
UID:nicar-2026-1012@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:From Boomers to Alphas\, there is currently a wider range of a
 ges than ever trying to create extraordinary journalism side-by-side durin
 g ever-changing and unprecedented times. Technology has created levels of 
 haves and have-nots\, digital natives and cultural luddites. But at the en
 d of the day\, our teams are here to serve our audiences and our communiti
 es: together. Let's talk about ways we can collaborate and find common gro
 und\, even when it feels sticky or difficult.\nParticipants will come away
  with a framework for collaborative decision-making and have the chance to
  roleplay in groups\, trying different mock scenarios among peers.\n\nCare
 er | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River I
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1012
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Master Class] Wanna get hired? Tales from the trenches
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T154500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T180000
UID:nicar-2026-1013@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:We're the hiring managers who've seen it all: the 11-page resu
 mes\, the glamorized headshots in applicant packages\, the ones that come 
 with a reference letter from Mom.\nWe also know what we're looking for whe
 n we get your materials\, and we're ready to spill out secrets. Come ask u
 s anything\, about resumes\, cover letters\, interviewing\, etc.\nParticip
 ants should walk away with an actionable tipsheet of ideas and ways to imp
 rove their job searching techniques and give their materials a boost.\n\nC
 areer | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:102
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1013
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Immigration data and how to make sense of it
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T113000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T123000
UID:nicar-2026-1018@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:The Trump administration has drastically reshaped immigration 
 enforcement. Newsrooms around the country are trying to make sense of what
  is happening to their communities. Join this panel to learn how reporters
  break down the most important immigration data sets and how that data can
  be used to tell both local and national stories.\n\nBeat reporting | Skil
 l: Beginner
LOCATION:White River G
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1018
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Demo] Utilizing new police misconduct and employment databases
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T090000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T100000
UID:nicar-2026-1021@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Learn about using new\, groundbreaking databases to track poli
 ce misconduct and employment histories: the Police Records Access Project 
 in California\, ACLU of West Virginia/Dragline's Police Accountability Das
 hboard\, the New York Police Disciplinary Records database\, and the Natio
 nal Police Index. This hands-on session will also briefly cover other rela
 ted police data projects around the country. This session is good for thos
 e with some experience using spreadsheets. Attendees will need to bring th
 eir own laptop (no tablets) to participate in this class.\n\nBeat reportin
 g\, Local\, Public records\, Research\, Tools & Tech\, Story ideas | Skill
 : Beginner
LOCATION:White River E
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1021
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Using data to find sources
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T113000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T123000
UID:nicar-2026-1022@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Data can provide context\, show trends\, and debunk false clai
 ms. But journalists don't always recognize its power to elevate even the m
 ore traditional parts of reporting. Data analysis can help you find human 
 sources (often with names and contact information in the spreadsheet itsel
 f). It can also help you pinpoint where to go for field reporting. We'll e
 xplore all these possibilities in this panel with a handful of examples yo
 u can take back to your newsroom.\n\nStory ideas | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River D
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1022
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Demo: The Gun Violence Data Hub
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T101500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T111500
UID:nicar-2026-1023@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Learn about the Gun Violence Data Hub\, an initiative from The
  Trace\, and how to use the data to report deeper and better stories in yo
 ur own community. The Data Hub provides resources for newsrooms to bolster
  their U.S. gun violence knowledge\, as well as an open data library of co
 ntextualized and well-documented datasets.\nThis session is good for those
  with some experience using spreadsheets. Attendees will need to bring the
 ir own laptop (no tablets) to participate in this class.\n\nData analysis\
 , Story ideas | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:202
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1023
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Connect with skeptical and disengaged audiences ... with d
 ata!
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T113000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T123000
UID:nicar-2026-1024@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Data journalists have a unique opportunity to reach skeptical 
 audiences who would otherwise reject established scientific facts. Let's h
 ighlight some journalistic endeavors to persuade and engage skeptical comm
 unities through innovative ways of presenting and explaining data.\n\nStor
 y ideas | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River G
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1024
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] How to scrape and analyze sports data in R to tell stor
 ies that stand out
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T143000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T153000
UID:nicar-2026-1025@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:There’s a lot of publicly available sports data.  How can yo
 u use those sources to build new datasets and tell compelling stories abou
 t what’s happening off the field? Learn how to quantify trends and debun
 k myths by leveling up your ability to scrape popular sports data websites
 \, then analyze that data in creative ways. Attendees will come away from 
 this hands-on session with experience scraping and analyzing data from the
  website Sports Reference\, which maintains data for all the major sports\
 , plus a better understanding of basic web-scraping concepts. Attendees sh
 ould have some familiarity with R and RStudio. Laptops will be provided.\n
 \nData analysis\, Sports | Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:104
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1025
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Customizing ggplot for yourself or your organization
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T101500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T111500
UID:nicar-2026-1026@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Imagine a version of ggplot that is customized to your organiz
 ation’s style guidelines\, in which you no longer have to write the same
  theme styling or geom_text layers every time you make a new chart. We’v
 e done that at Pew Research Center by writing our own graphics package mad
 e up of functions that modify\, combine and extend existing ggplot functio
 ns (wrappers)\, and we want to share what we learned!\nAttendees will leav
 e the session knowing how to get much closer to publication-ready graphics
  without leaving R\, in far fewer lines of code. For those who may want to
  go beyond streamlining their own personal ggplot use\, we’ll also go ov
 er why (or why not) a custom R graphics package could be the right solutio
 n for their organizations — and how to start building one if it is.\nAtt
 endees should have some familiarity with R and RStudio. Laptops will be pr
 ovided.\n\nData analysis\, Data viz\, Tools & Tech | Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:205
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1026
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Fun with hypotheticals: Investigating your dubious data di
 lemmas in real time
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T143000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T153000
UID:nicar-2026-1031@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:From the people who dared to ask “How many rats are in the R
 ainforest Cafe?” at NICAR25 comes an interactive panel on approaching a 
 data story with an investigative mindset — this year done in real time. 
 Attendees are encouraged to submit their most ridiculous investigative que
 stions ahead of and during the panel. As a group\, we’ll take a few of t
 hose questions and propose and refine a hypothesis\, make a reporting plan
 \, brainstorm records requests\, and more. By the end of the session\, par
 ticipants will be equipped to craft an investigative data story from scrat
 ch — starting from even the most unexpected or whimsical question. Submi
 t your ideas at https://tinyurl.com/hypotheticals26.\n\nStory ideas\, trac
 ks | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River E
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1031
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] How to use AI responsibly
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T143000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T153000
UID:nicar-2026-1034@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Journalists across the world are trying to determine how and w
 hen to use GenAI and other machine learning techniques for reporting. Pane
 lists from a range of projects and newsrooms will discuss how they conside
 red journalistic ethics while using AI. Attendees should leave with ideas 
 on when to combine AI classification with manual review\, what to disclose
  to audiences and other practical tips.\n\nAI | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River D
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1034
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Challenges with cross-domain collaboration
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T154500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T164500
UID:nicar-2026-1035@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:As newsrooms shrink more journalists are collaborating with ac
 ademics\, nonprofit organizations and other groups for investigations. Whi
 le collaborating allows us to do work we couldn’t otherwise\, they also 
 come with specific challenges. What do you do when stakeholders want diffe
 rent things? Or when one team isn’t able to deliver what was promised?\n
 \nStory ideas | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River B
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1035
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Enhancing public records work with LLMs
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T143000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T153000
UID:nicar-2026-1036@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Explore the Python libraries for the MuckRock Requests and Doc
 umentCloud APIs and how they can be used with large language models (LLMs)
  to streamline records requests assist in analyzing responsive documents.\
 nParticipants will also be introduced to llm-documentcloud\, a plugin for 
 LLM command-line tool/Python library that enables feeding documents for an
 alysis in various LLMs for analysis. The session will cover strategies for
  crafting clearer\, more effective public records requests\, as well as te
 chniques for summarizing\, organizing\, and extracting data and insights f
 rom responsive documents. Attendees are encouraged to bring their own proj
 ects\, ideas\, and questions for exploration.\nThis session is good for th
 ose with some Python experience. Attendees will need to bring their own la
 ptop (no tablets) to participate in this class.\n\nAI\, Public records\, T
 ools & Tech | Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:202
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1036
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Demo] Data investigation frameworks: How to think big picture abo
 ut what your data will prove
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T170000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T180000
UID:nicar-2026-1038@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:In investigative journalism\, data often provides the core evi
 dence to hold powerful actors accountable — proving wrongdoing\, harm or
  scale. But how can you know what data tools and skills you’ll need when
  you start an investigation? This session will break down the basic struct
 ure of a data investigation\, outlining a few frameworks for how data prov
 ides that proof. We won’t focus on specific tools — the best tool for 
 the job will be different for every story. Instead\, we’ll practice how 
 to think about using data to strengthen an investigation\, so that you kno
 w exactly what questions you want data to answer before you spend time fin
 ding and analyzing it. This session will include audience participation an
 d is well-suited to early career journalists or anyone seeking to get more
  comfortable with thinking and planning for data-based investigative repor
 ting.\n\nCareer\, Data analysis | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River I
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1038
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Data in the world of audio
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T154500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T164500
UID:nicar-2026-1039@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Are you a data-oriented reporter working at a public radio sta
 tion? Interested in presenting findings from a data-driven investigation o
 n a podcast or talk show? This session will debunk the common saying heard
  in many public radio newsrooms that "numbers and radio don't mix." This p
 anel will provide practical tips on how to effectively present data-driven
  reporting in different audio mediums\, ranging from long-form podcasts to
  short-form newscasts. It'll also be a open forum for discussing how repor
 ters have found creative ways to put data journalism on air.\n\nData analy
 sis\, AI | Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:White River D
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1039
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Introduction to network visualization and analysis
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T143000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T153000
UID:nicar-2026-1041@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:A hands-on walkthrough of an entire network visualization work
 flow. Starting with processing the data\, converting it into a network for
 mat\, laying it out in Gephi\, and visualizing it using one of several vis
 ualization libraries (Holoviews\, Sigma.js\, Cosmograph\, etc). While disc
 ussing different choices throughout the process (aggregation\, layout algo
 rithm\, filtering\, etc.) and their impact on the visualization.\nThis ses
 sion is good for those with experience working with data and visualization
  libraries. Attendees will need to bring their own laptop (no tablets) to 
 participate in this class.\n\nData viz | Skill: Advanced
LOCATION:201
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1041
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Making better databases with Airtable
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T154500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T164500
UID:nicar-2026-1043@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Airtable is a spreadsheet and database software with useful fe
 atures to view\, sort\, group\, and link records between tables. You'll se
 e a few examples of how Airtable has been useful for the instructor's repo
 rting (and why she almost never use Excel anymore!) and walk through a han
 ds-on example.\nThis session is good for: Anyone who has been frustrated a
 t making multiple versions of the same spreadsheet\, creating extra column
 s (or filters) and then repeatedly hiding and unhiding them\, or jumping b
 etween multiple spreadsheets to bring together different information about
  the same record.\nThis session is good for people with basic experience w
 orking with data. Attendees will need to bring their own laptop (no tablet
 s).\n\nData analysis | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:209
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1043
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] The price of recovery: How to investigate opioid settlemen
 t spending
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T090000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T100000
UID:nicar-2026-1045@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:As states\, counties\, cities\, and tribes begin spending more
  than $80 billion in opioid settlement funds\, questions of transparency a
 nd accountability are increasingly urgent. In this session\, five graduate
  students from West Virginia University’s Reed School of Media will shar
 e how they used investigative and data reporting techniques to track settl
 ement spending in their state – and how this approach can be replicated 
 in your communities! Panelists will outline key strategies for data collec
 tion\, open records requests\, and newsroom partnerships\, while reflectin
 g on journalism’s role in holding institutions accountable and amplifyin
 g community voices in responses to the opioid crisis.\n\nBeat reporting\, 
 Students\, Story ideas | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River B
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1045
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Teaching data journalism in the AI era
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T143000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T153000
UID:nicar-2026-1050@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:As journalists\, we spend years learning how to navigate data 
 of all kinds and keep our investigations on track. Now students can ask an
  LLM to write their code or summarize a dataset in seconds... and get some
 thing back that looks right. Or let generative AI drive their assumptions 
 about data without doing enough reporting. So how do we actually teach the
 se foundational skills? While there's no finished playbook for this yet (o
 r even consensus within individual schools or journalism departments)\, th
 is panel will work through classroom strategies that let you use AI tools 
 without short-circuiting critical thinking. We'll also get into which conc
 erns about AI are real problems and which are overblown\, plus where it mi
 ght genuinely help students learn. You'll walk away with things to try in 
 your next class\, whether it's a new course or a curricular refresh.\n\nAI
 \, Story ideas\, Data analysis | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River I
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1050
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Using coding agents for data analysis
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T143000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T180000
UID:nicar-2026-1053@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:PLEASE NOTE: The instructor for this class will be teaching vi
 a Zoom. TA's will be present in the class to provide hands-on assistance.\
 nCoding agents such as Claude Code and OpenAI Codex are mainly marketed at
  developers\, but they're actually applicable to a much wider array of pro
 blems\, including data analysis\, data cleaning\, web scraping and other t
 asks commonly faced by data journalists.\nIn this session\, you'll learn h
 ow to apply these tools to both simple and ambitious data reporting projec
 ts. Attendees will go away with a very powerful new tool for collecting\, 
 exploring\, analyzing and presenting data.\nLaptops will be provided.\n\nA
 I | Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:104
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1053
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Auditing AI algorithms for bias (and sometimes using AI to
 ols to do so)
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T090000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T100000
UID:nicar-2026-1054@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:AI is everywhere and reporters are finding new ways to hold AI
  tools accountable\, sometimes using AI to do so. This panel will discuss 
 how journalists can identify bias in predictive and generative AI tools bu
 ilt by some of the largest technology companies\, plus speakers will share
  which AI tools they use for investigations and research.\n\nAI | Skill: I
 ntermediate
LOCATION:White River E
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1054
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] How to educate journalism students about AI and with AI
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T113000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T123000
UID:nicar-2026-1055@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Artificial intelligence is here to stay\, so it’s important 
 to have a plan in place to educate the next generation of journalists. Thi
 s panel of journalists and educators will hold a town hall-style session t
 o share strategies and ideas on effective ways to educate journalism stude
 nts about AI. Attendees will learn about what has and hasn't worked\, how 
 to use and build tools and how to be ethical and accountable when using AI
 .\n\nAI\, Educators | Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:White River I
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1055
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Demo] Use our quiz to focus on policy\, not politics\, in 2026
DTSTART;TZID=EDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260308T090000
DTEND;TZID=EDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260308T100000
UID:nicar-2026-1058@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Help your audience prioritize public policy over political par
 ty or personality in the 2026 elections with QuizTheVote. It will transfor
 m your existing candidate questionnaires into an interactive quiz in about
  an hour. We'll talk about how to prepare for and implement QuizTheVote\, 
 an open source resource built on Google sheets with no coding required.\n\
 nElections | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River B
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1058
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Analyzing election data with Polars and Python
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T170000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T180000
UID:nicar-2026-1061@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Polars is a modern dataframe library for Python that’s fast\
 , focussed\, and easy to use. At the Financial Times\, Polars has been an 
 essential component in our live election results pipelines and our computa
 tional investigations.\nPolars has many advantages over the older pandas d
 ataframe library\, including speed and type safety. But perhaps the bigges
 t benefit is that it has a simple\, logical\, and memorable API that makes
  it much more enjoyable to use. Working with tabular data in Polars feels 
 as easy and expressive as it does with R’s tidyverse.\nIn this session w
 e will use election results data to teach the fundamentals of analysing ta
 bular data with Polars\, including:\n•⁠  ⁠Loading and saving data\n
 •⁠  ⁠Selecting columns\n•⁠  ⁠Filtering rows\n•⁠  ⁠Sortin
 g dataframes\n•⁠  ⁠Creating new columns by combining and calculating
  values from existing columns\n•⁠  ⁠Grouping rows and aggregating th
 eir data\n•⁠  ⁠Using joins to combine two or more dataframes\nWe wil
 l teach these skills through examples of how we have used the library in o
 riginal data journalism work.\nThis session is good for people with Python
  experience. Laptops will be provided.\n\nData analysis | Skill: Intermedi
 ate
LOCATION:104
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1061
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Finding the story in higher education data
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T143000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T153000
UID:nicar-2026-1062@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:From campus speech policies to federal funding cuts\, higher e
 ducation is in the headlines now more than ever. As former reporting inter
 ns for The Chronicle of Higher Education\, we’ll lead a lightning round 
 on data sources we used to cover some of the hottest stories in higher ed:
  from the fall of affirmative action to a state-mandated purge of general 
 education courses.\nThis session is ideal for student journalists\, and us
 eful for any reporter covering the education beat. Attendees will need to 
 bring their own laptop (no tablets) to participate in this class.\n\nBeat 
 reporting\, Story ideas | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:102
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1062
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] 10 things you didn’t know you could do in R
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T154500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T180000
UID:nicar-2026-1063@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:R is great for quick data exploration\, visualization and spat
 ial analysis. But did you know you can extract text from images\, send cus
 tomized emails and chat with PDFs all without ever leaving the cozy comfor
 t of R?\nIn this session\, we'll zip through a few lesser-known or relativ
 ely new R packages for working with large language models\, media and data
 bases. Though pitched at intermediate users interested in getting more mil
 eage out of R\, this demo will also give beginners a taste of what's possi
 ble. As a bonus\, we'll invite attendees to complete a short survey sharin
 g some of the unexpected ways they use R in their newsrooms and circulate 
 the results in a tip sheet after the session.\nThis session is good for pe
 ople with some experience working with R. Laptops will be provided.\n\nDat
 a analysis\, Tools & Tech | Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:204
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1063
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Using open-source tools to investigate public transit
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T113000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T123000
UID:nicar-2026-1064@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Public transit systems offer a treasure trove of data that can
  reveal vital insights into accessibility\, equity\, and efficiency. Toget
 her\, we’ll learn how to harness the data that powers tools like Google 
 Maps and explore how these datasets can be used to investigate service cov
 erage\, travel times\, and on-time performance. Whether you're uncovering 
 how well a city serves its residents or tracking disparities in service qu
 ality\, this session will arm you with the skills to transform transit dat
 a into compelling stories.\nThis session is good for those with some sprea
 dsheets experience. Laptops will be provided.\n\nBeat reporting\, Story id
 eas\, Tools & Tech | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:205
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1064
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Building your first SvelteKit data app
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T143000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T153000
UID:nicar-2026-1065@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:SvelteKit is a user-friendly JavaScript framework that allows 
 you to easily build and deploy web apps. Join us for a crash course in usi
 ng SvelteKit to make a data-driven interactive.\nThis session is great for
  those with frontend development knowledge. Laptops will be provided.\n\nT
 ools & Tech | Skill: Advanced
LOCATION:205
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1065
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Scraping without programming
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T143000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T153000
UID:nicar-2026-1068@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:"Scraping" is a catch-all word for grabbing information off a 
 web page and into your spreadsheet - whether the website wants you to or n
 ot. This session will introduce easy\, hands-on methods for scraping data 
 from a live webpage without having to learn any code. We will use the Impo
 rtHTML and ImportXML formulas in Google Sheets.\nScraping beginners welcom
 e! Attendees will need to bring their own laptop (no tablets) to participa
 te in this class.\n\nData analysis\, Tools & Tech | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:202
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1068
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Using data to investigate the global surveillance industry
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T090000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T100000
UID:nicar-2026-1069@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Around the world\, shadowy firms are siphoning location data f
 rom apps\, telecom networks\, and rogue brokers to track people with chill
 ing precision. Whether it’s journalists\, Silicon Valley executives\, or
  visitors to Jeffrey Epstein’s island\, no one is off-limits. This panel
  brings together journalists who have exposed how invisible surveillance i
 nfrastructure is being used to follow people worldwide—and how little st
 ands in the way. The journalists will explain how they uncovered these sto
 ries\, how they obtained covert datasets through techniques ranging from i
 dentifying misconfigured cloud storage buckets to scouring undocumented AP
 Is. They’ll break down how journalists can use data to expose the inner 
 workings of the shadowy tracking systems and offer practical methods for i
 nvestigating the rapidly expanding global surveillance industry.\n\nData a
 nalysis\, Data viz\, Beat reporting | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River E
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1069
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Finding the story: Trade data
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T101500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T111500
UID:nicar-2026-1070@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:As trade and tariffs become an increasingly relevant issue\, t
 his session will demo a free (but very unintuitive) tool from the U.S. Cen
 sus: USA Trade! USA Trade has comprehensive\, district-level data (with lo
 ts of hidden gems) that can be useful for data journalists across beats\, 
 especially those relating to global economics\, trade\, tech\, and foreign
  policy. This session will demonstrate how to use USA Trade and discuss so
 me ways to understand and use the data in your reporting. This session is 
 good for everyone interested in learning more about trade stats.\nNo data 
 experience is necessary! Attendees will need to bring their own laptops (p
 referably no tablets) for the training.\n\nBeat reporting | Skill: Beginne
 r
LOCATION:201
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1070
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Elevate your graphics with Illustrator!
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T101500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T111500
UID:nicar-2026-1071@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Illustrator is a great tool for creating beautiful\, completel
 y unique data viz and graphics – but the best part is it doesn’t need 
 to all be done from scratch. In this session\, we will go over ways to beg
 in making your chart using various online tools that most newsrooms alread
 y use (like Datawrapper\, RawGraphs\, Flourish\, ggplot\, etc.) but elevat
 e its design with the magic of SVGs and vector graphics programs like Adob
 e Illustrator. We’ll talk through color choices\, fonts\, accessibility\
 , framing\, and more – and give you tips and tricks to create stunning g
 raphics that you can customize to your heart’s delight.\nThis session is
  good for beginners. Attendees will need to bring their own laptop (no tab
 lets) to participate in this class.\n\nData viz | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:202
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1071
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Tips to investigate influencers and live-streamers
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T090000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T100000
UID:nicar-2026-1075@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:This session centers around the tools used for three recent st
 ories involving video analysis.\nThe reporting subjects include a deep div
 e into livestreamers promoting crypto casinos\, political podcasters in th
 e run-up to the 2024 U.S. Presidential Election and linking the advertiser
 s propping up right-wing influencers.\nThrough these case studies\, we wil
 l highlight tools to archive videos\, inspect metadata\, analyze transcrip
 ts\, map guest networks\, and detect text and objects in video.\nCome lear
 n some new tools for your next investigation!\n\nBeat reporting\, Story id
 eas | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River D
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1075
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Think spatially: Finding stories in geographic data wit
 h geopandas
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T154500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T164500
UID:nicar-2026-1078@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Geographic data can do more than make pretty maps—it can hel
 p you find stories. In this hands-on session\, you’ll learn how to use G
 eopandas\, a Python tool that lets you work with location data just like y
 ou work with spreadsheets. We’ll focus on how to ask and answer reportin
 g questions with geographic data: Which neighborhoods have the most pothol
 es? Which schools are near industrial sites? Where do service gaps overlap
 ?\nYou’ll learn how to combine and compare different datasets\, look for
  patterns and boundaries\, and measure what’s happening where. We’ll a
 lso look briefly at how to show your results on a map\, but the main goal 
 is to help you use location data for analysis—not just visualization.\nT
 his session is good for people with experience working with Python. Laptop
 s will be provided.\n\nMapping\, Tools & Tech | Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:205
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1078
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Demo] Rubric-a-palooza
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T143000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T153000
UID:nicar-2026-1086@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:At this demo party\, we’ll discuss the Science of Teaching a
 nd Learning (SoTL) behind effective ways to give students feedback. Ideall
 y\, we’ll learn tips and tricks from one another as well as from the lit
 erature and do a hands-on exercise using AI tools to help us write effecti
 ve rubrics for our assignments.\n\nEducators | Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:209
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1086
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Automating mass scraping with AI
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T090000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T100000
UID:nicar-2026-1087@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:This session will explore tools to create scrapers and structu
 red data from websites with the help of LLMs. Scraping data off the web is
  not new for journalists\, but what about when the data is spread out acro
 ss hundreds of websites in dozens of formats? Writing and maintaining flee
 ts of scrapers may have previously required a team of data journalists\, b
 ut new methods allow us to use LLMs to analyze the structure of a website 
 and automatically generate a working scraper. This means we can pursue sto
 ries involving more ambitious data collection on deadline.\nIn this sessio
 n\, we will demonstrate a package we built at the Tow Center for Digital J
 ournalism called “Scraper Factory\,” which uses LLMs to write Python s
 crapers. We will discuss stories where we have used this approach and soli
 cit input from the community on best practices and innovations with these 
 new methods.\nThis session is good for those who have a familiarity of the
  command line\, basic scraping skills\, and are wanting to work in Python.
  Laptops will be provided. You will need a GitHub account to participate.\
 n\nAI | Skill: Advanced
LOCATION:104
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1087
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Clustering and mapping text data for journalism
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T143000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T153000
UID:nicar-2026-1088@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Analysis of large text datasets can be difficult\, and finding
  story ideas can be even harder\, especially when you’re not sure what y
 ou’re looking for. This session teaches you to explore large sets of doc
 uments using semantic maps—visual clusters with similar documents groupe
 d together in a two-dimensional chart. Users will learn how to convert tex
 t documents into embeddings\, visualize them in two dimensions\, and explo
 re the data for insights by applying filters by keyword or time period. Ap
 plications include: parsing FOIA responses\, tracking similar legislative 
 language\, or finding new areas of concern in school board comments.\nPart
 icipants will leave with the ability to map and cluster a sample of text d
 ata with provided code. This session is good for those with some Python ex
 perience. Laptops will be provided. You will need a GitHub account to part
 icipate.\n\nData analysis | Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:104
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1088
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Using immigration data to tell stories in your communit
 y
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T090000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T100000
UID:nicar-2026-1089@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:There's no shortage of data that can help you tell local stori
 es on the sprawling immigration beat\, but the data are often scattered\, 
 inconsistent and come with lots of caveats. This hands-on session will wal
 k you through telling a data-driven story on asylum rates in your city or 
 state\, from gathering the data to analyzing it. We'll also give you an ov
 erview of other immigration data sources to help you tell stories on how p
 olicies out of Washington impact your community — from immigration enfor
 cement to the court system.\nThis session's instructors are fluent in both
  Python and R. Code in both languages will be provided and instructors wil
 l be able to assist attendees following along in either language. The clas
 s will be taught in whichever language the majority of attendees vote for 
 at the start of the session!\n\nBeat reporting\, Data analysis\, Local\, P
 ublic records\, Story ideas | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:102
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1089
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Demo] How to investigate Telegram
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T101500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T111500
UID:nicar-2026-1091@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:A session that shows participants a variety of tools and trick
 s for investigating Telegram chats and channels. Telegram is a primary sou
 rce for a lot of newsworthy activity: militias in armed conflicts around t
 he world\, neo-Nazi terror organizations\, illicit markets\, etc. Telegram
  also has a very open and accessible API\, which makes fetching and workin
 g with their data easier than many other social media platforms. But there
 's a lot of features of and knowledge about Telegram that often isn't alwa
 ys apparent\, which can cause pitfalls for journalists and researchers who
  aren't familiar with it.\n\nBeat reporting\, Data analysis\, Research\, S
 tory ideas\, Tools & Tech | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:102
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1091
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] How to scrape an entire social media platform
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T113000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T123000
UID:nicar-2026-1092@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:There's an interesting "alt" social media platform called pill
 ed.net\, which is popular in the conspiracy theory community. It has an AP
 I that's straightforward to engineer\, and it has only about 1 million pos
 ts. So it's possible to fairly easily create a scraper\, then scrape and a
 nalyze the entire platform.\nThe sessions will show how to reverse enginee
 r a social media platform's APIs\, how to implement a scraper in Python\, 
 how to use the scraper to collect all the data\, and then a few high-level
  analyses that can be done on the data.\nThis session is good for those wi
 th some working with Python. Laptops will be provided.\n\nTools & Tech | S
 kill: Advanced
LOCATION:104
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1092
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Using open-source intelligence (OSINT) in investigations
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T101500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T111500
UID:nicar-2026-1094@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:This session will show how journalists can begin incorporating
  open-source research methodologies in their investigations\, with example
 s from real articles.\n\nResearch | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River E
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1094
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Accessibility basics
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T101500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T111500
UID:nicar-2026-1096@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Come to this session for a crash course in some of the issues 
 to consider when meeting basic accessibility requirements for digital news
 . Panelists will discuss topics including color accessibility\, alt text\,
  mouseless navigation\, and more.\n\nEquity\, inclusion and accessibility 
 | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River E
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1096
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] From satellites to stories: Leveraging Google Earth Eng
 ine to analyze global environmental datasets for local reporting
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T143000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T153000
UID:nicar-2026-1098@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Accessing openly published maps and models from the latest res
 earch has never been easier through platforms like Google Earth Engine (GE
 E)\, enabling journalists to expose systemic patterns of environmental har
 m at scale—including those not already captured in government statistics
 —while honing in on\, based on data\, the most salient case studies for 
 detailed ground reporting.\nIn this session\, you will learn how to access
  the forest change dataset powering Global Forest Watch for free through G
 EE with just one line of code. You’ll then quantify changes to forests i
 n a local area and\, most importantly\, analyze this remotely sensed data 
 together with detailed local data to illuminate impacts of environmental c
 hange on communities.\nYou'll need to sign up for a few things. Get a head
  start by visiting our tipsheet at\nhttp://tiny.cc/nicar-gee\nThis session
  is good for those with some experience working with geospatial data. Atte
 ndees will need to bring their own laptop (no tablets) to participate in t
 his class.\n\nMapping\, Data analysis\, Tools & Tech | Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:201
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1098
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] AI agents and pipelines with no-code tools
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T170000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T180000
UID:nicar-2026-1101@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Want an automatic digest of news on your beat or what your cit
 y council has been up to? Get pinged on Slack with a summary when an edito
 r takes a pass at your story?  All without touching a line of code?\nIn th
 is session we'll learn to use no-code AI pipeline tools like n8n and Activ
 ePieces to automate journalistic processes. Learn what agents and pipeline
 s are\, what they do\, and the bevy of vocabulary and technical terms you'
 ll need to put your own workflows to... work!\n- What APIs are and how the
 y can supercharge your workflow\n- Schedule monthly\, weekly\, or hourly a
 utomatic processes\n- How to set up and use webhooks to trigger actions\n-
  Differences between providers and models\n- Unraveling technical settings
  like temperature and structured output\nParticipants will learn the funda
 mental basics of how no-code AI pipeline tools work and integrate with oth
 er services\, and will be well-prepared to start exploring on their own.\n
 This session is good for people with some experience working with data. At
 tendees will need to bring their own laptop (no tablets) to participate in
  this class.\n\nAI | Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:202
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1101
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Modern document processing with Natural PDF
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T154500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T164500
UID:nicar-2026-1106@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Writing Python scripts to extract data from PDFs is always a n
 ightmare - misshapen tables\, arbitrary form formatting\, tiny text or low
 -quality scanned texts. Your champion is here in the form of Natural PDF\,
  a new Python library for wrangling data that's focused on usability and c
 ramming in as many features as possible. Write your code just like you'd a
 sk "real-language" questions:\n- "Find the bold text that ends with a colo
 n and get the text to the right of it"\n- "Show me all pages that include 
 diagrams"\n- "Ignore everything above the thick horizontal line"\nNatural 
 PDF also comes bundled with all sorts of modern AI-based magic:\n- Categor
 ize pages or entire PDFs by text or vision models\n- Use powerful layout a
 nalysis engines to recognize images\, tables\, headers\, and paragraphs\n-
  Multilingual OCR powered by multiple engines + LLM-correcting integration
 \nParticipants will leave with a solid understanding of how to extract dat
 a from difficult (and simple) PDFs using Python.\nThis session is good for
  those with some experience working with Python. Laptops will be provided.
 \n\nAI\, Tools & Tech | Skill: Advanced
LOCATION:104
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1106
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Demo] Analyzing images and videos with AI
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T101500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T111500
UID:nicar-2026-1107@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Tools like facial recognition\, red-light/speed cameras and cr
 owd-counting have long been the territory of locked-up\, super-secret algo
 rithms from private industry and government. But no longer! Learn how to u
 se open-source tools like the Python library supervision and open-source m
 odels to unlock real-world analysis abilities. Automate analysis of almost
  everything – from satellite imagery to TikTok videos – and unlock lev
 els of small-team investigation that were impossible just a few years ago.
 \nLearn how AI can sort through images and video to help you wrangle foota
 ge from protests and riots (NYT)\, analyze trends on TikTok (Washington Po
 st)\, keep an eye on your local school board meetings (Hearst)\, measure t
 he effects of congestion pricing (Bloomberg)\, and a hundred other tidbits
  for when the cameras might be rolling.\nWith a little Python and a dash o
 f foundational knowledge\, this session will tackle downloading videos\, b
 uilding and evaluating transcripts\, splitting scenes\, categorizing image
 s\, and detecting/counting/tracking objects.\n\nAI | Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:White River D
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1107
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Scraping dynamic websites with browser automation tools
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T101500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T111500
UID:nicar-2026-1109@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Playwright is a next-generation browser automation tool that a
 llows you to use Python or JavaScript to scrape almost any web page. It ca
 n assist in downloading pages of government documents\, capturing tweets b
 efore they get deleted\, or even just breaking past the cookie consent ban
 ner. Beyond the basics\, it can also easily take screenshots\, monitor and
  log network requests\, and even fit right into your traditional Beautiful
 Soup scraping approach.\nWe'll look at:\n- Installing Playwright\n- Access
 ing elements on the page\n- Interacting with web pages (clicking\, navigat
 ing\, filling out forms)\n- Taking screenshots\n- Sending pages to traditi
 onal scraping tools like BeautifulSoup\n- Common patterns including pagina
 tion and CAPTCHA breaking\nFor those of you familiar with tackling similar
  problems using Selenium: Playwright is a similar tool with a better inter
 face\, better install/upgrade process\, and ten times the usability. It mi
 ght be time to upgrade!\nParticipants should have a basic knowledge of Pyt
 hon and HTML\, but we'll also cover how to breeze past those basics with A
 I assistance. Attendees will need to bring their own laptop (no tablets) t
 o participate in this class.\n\nData analysis\, Tools & Tech | Skill: Inte
 rmediate
LOCATION:201
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1109
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Automating your workflows with Github Actions
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T113000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T123000
UID:nicar-2026-1110@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:There are a ton of routine data sets that we pull regularly to
  analyze. Crime\, housing\, construction. But what if you could do that wh
 ile you sleep? Github Actions allows you to do just that.\nParticipants sh
 ould have a basic knowledge of Github. Attendees will need to bring their 
 own laptop (no tablets) to participate in this class.\n\nTools & Tech | Sk
 ill: Intermediate
LOCATION:202
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1110
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] How to categorize and clean text data with keywords\, LLMs
  and embeddings: A roundtable
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T154500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T164500
UID:nicar-2026-1111@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Our datasets are often not just numbers but free-text descript
 ions -- AI chatbot logs\, TikTok transcripts or government contract purpos
 es. Three-ish reporters discuss how to categorize this kind of text data w
 ith three very different techniques: ol' fashioned keywords\, embeddings a
 nd LLMs. We'll discuss the trade-offs between cost\, precision and recall 
 and interpretability -- and of course tell some war stories. We'll also di
 scuss how to come up with taxonomies that make sense and how to refine eac
 h technique.\n\nAI | Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:White River I
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1111
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Free or cheap web-scraping tools – no coding required
 !
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T170000
