BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] From chaos to narrative: Using R for story discovery in
  document collections
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T154500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T164500
UID:nicar-2026-1127@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:This session will introduce journalists to using R to ingest l
 arge numbers of lawsuits\, transcripts\, news articles and similar materia
 l and to discover story leads through content analysis methods. Journalist
 s will learn the benefits and drawbacks of sentiment analysis\, keyword in
  context text retrievals\, language dependency parsing\, and extraction of
  top two- and three-word phrases. These tools in R's tidytext package can 
 help reporters discover themes and tips in large groups of documents that 
 otherwise could do undetected.\nThis session is good for those with some e
 xperience using R. Attendees will need to bring their own laptop (no table
 ts) to participate in this class.\n\nTools & Tech\, Story ideas | Skill: I
 ntermediate
LOCATION:203
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1127
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Next-gen crime data: Know your NIBRS!
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T143000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T153000
UID:nicar-2026-1129@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Forget murder\, robbery and burglary. Do you know how many ATM
  thefts your local police logged last year? Or carjackings? Or stalking ca
 ses? Most police agencies now log a wealth of detail on 58 crimes via the 
 National Incident-Based Reporting. Learn how to get started using this inv
 aluable but complicated data.\n\nTools & Tech\, Research\, Data analysis |
  Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:White River I
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1129
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Editing the machine: Fact-checking AI-assisted reporting i
 n the newsroom
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T090000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T100000
UID:nicar-2026-1130@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:As AI tools move into daily reporting\, the real challenge isn
 't keeping up with the hype\, it's the editing. This session is focused on
  the real editorial challenges that come up when you're responsible for pe
 ople\, data\, ethics\, and deadlines all at once—and AI is ambient and o
 ften invisible. This isn’t a heady conversation about the future of AI i
 n journalism\, ethics boards or tech tips. It’s meant to focus on what's
  already changed and how that shows up in newsroom decision-making.\nThe g
 oal is to move beyond the abstract and talk about everyday editorial decis
 ions. What feels different in copy review? In sourcing? In data analysis? 
 Where do editors need to slow down\, ask a different question\, or reopen 
 a framing that might have quietly solidified? This is about how editorial 
 judgment evolves when AI is in the workflow.\n\nAI | Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:White River B
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1130
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Detangling federal lobbying disclosures with LobbyR
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T143000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T153000
UID:nicar-2026-1131@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Political influence is getting harder and harder to track\, bu
 t the Lobbying Disclosure Act Reports helps cut through some of the noise.
  With LobbyR\, researchers\, journalists\, and others can easily access\, 
 clean\, and visualize a much more comprehensive version of federal lobbyin
 g disclosures to understand what companies\, groups and other interests ar
 e asking Congress and the administration for.\nIn this session\, you’ll 
 learn how just a few lines of R code will allow you to query\, summarize\,
  and plot real-world lobbying transparency data\, enabling rapid insights 
 and automated workflows. And there's no complex setup required.\nIf you wa
 nt to ask questions like “who lobbied on issue X in the last five years?
 ”\, or “how many dollars did registrant Y report?”\, or “are there
  clients/registrants filing that overlap?”\, LobbyR makes this work prog
 rammatic\, reproducible\, and transparent.\nParticipants should have a bas
 ic knowledge of R. Laptops will be provided. Participants should pre-regis
 ter for an API key through this link: https://lda.gov/api/register/\n\nToo
 ls & Tech\, Research\, Story ideas | Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:204
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1131
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Demo] Nonprofit data 101
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T113000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T123000
UID:nicar-2026-1133@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:There's a good nonprofit story waiting to be written on every 
 reporting beat and in every coverage area\, if you know where to look. Thi
 s session will teach you how to navigate the world of nonprofit data and d
 ocuments.\nTo gain tax-exempt status\, organizations like hospitals\, char
 ter schools\, colleges and humane societies must agree to report annual in
 formation on their finances\, compensation of key personnel\, conflicts of
  interest and more. If you know how to cut through the accounting language
  to find what you're looking for\, these annual filings — and other docu
 ments generated by a nonprofit — can answer questions big and small and 
 add useful context to your reporting.\n\nBeat reporting\, Story ideas | Sk
 ill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River I
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1133
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Coaching ChatGPT to help with coding and data tasks
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T113000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T123000
UID:nicar-2026-1136@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:ChatGPT\, widely misunderstood and in some cases misused\, can
  be a powerful tool to improve efficiency in our day-to-day work. Give Cha
 tGPT a few rows of publicly available data and ask it to write a data dict
 ionary. We'll use ChatGPT to help write a public records request for us\, 
 have it help us make sense of data and we'll even use it to write a Python
  script to reshape unruly Excel data. The best part? You don't need to kno
 w Python to write this code.\nThis session is good for everyone. Attendees
  will need to bring their own laptop (no tablets).\n\nAI | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:102
