BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Reporting on maternal and infant health in turbulent times
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T101500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T111500
UID:nicar-2026-1158@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:The U.S. has the highest maternal mortality rate of any high-i
 ncome nation\, with stark differences within the U.S. along racial and geo
 graphic lines. Early evidence suggests that system shocks like Covid and s
 tate-level abortion bans may have made pregnancy and childbirth even more 
 dangerous. Meanwhile\, the Trump administration has slashed public health 
 initiatives\, altered childhood vaccine schedules and gutted many federal 
 data collection projects\, including those focusing on maternal and infant
  health outcomes.\nThis panel will explore the ways we can use available d
 ata to report on maternal and infant health\, and discuss ways we can cont
 inue this work at the state\, regional and national level despite the loss
  of some federal data sources.\n\nBeat reporting\, Story ideas | Skill: Be
 ginner
LOCATION:White River E
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1158
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Demo] State secrets: A workflow for using state-level ethics disc
 losure data in your reporting
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T090000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T100000
UID:nicar-2026-1160@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Learn how to find and use personal financial and economic inte
 rest disclosures to report on candidates and elected officials in every st
 ate. We’ll demo digging into two state systems\, share collaborative dat
 asets available to participants and a comprehensive tipsheet on what data 
 is available in each state in 2026\, and run through tips on how to track 
 changes and new filings.\nReporters with basic Python skills will be able 
 to follow along\, but all attendees can benefit from the discussion of ope
 n data and workflow-building using these public documents. Participants wi
 ll leave better prepared and kitted out to do strong accountability report
 ing on candidates and incumbents in significant elections across the count
 ry in 2026. We'll also discuss how these records can be used for deeper in
 vestigations into business connections\, real estate\, environmental issue
 s and more.\n\nLocal\, Public records\, Research\, Elections | Skill: Inte
 rmediate
LOCATION:102
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1160
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[NICAR Conversation] Continuous improvement for reporters: Kaizen\
 , preflight checklists and more
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T154500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T164500
UID:nicar-2026-1161@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Let’s talk about how we can make reviewing and improving our
  work and our recurring processes (both automated and manual) a core part 
 of our workflow as reporters and editors. Panelists will discuss goal sett
 ing\, review and improvement processes like the "plan act do check" cycle\
 , the broader philosophy of growth through incremental change and document
 ation\, and how systems used in manufacturing\, aviation\, tech and other 
 industries can be adapted for reporters\, especially when it comes to data
  and investigative work. This won't just be hypothetical: we'll discuss pr
 actical ways to turn these systems and philosophies into real-world workfl
 ows for both freelance and staff journalists.\n\nStory ideas | Skill: Begi
 nner
LOCATION:209
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1161
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Data team starter kit: How to build a data team from the g
 round up
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T090000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T100000
UID:nicar-2026-1165@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:How do you set a new data team up for success? How do you grow
  a data team while maintaining your team's identity and standards? This se
 ssion will tackle best practices for establishing and maintaining standard
 s on new and growing data teams. We'll cover automating onboarding\, stand
 ardizing project structure with Datakit and setting up a robust fact-check
 ing process.\n\nCareer | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River D
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1165
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] “Vibe-coding” for experimentation and deadlines
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T154500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T164500
UID:nicar-2026-1168@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Picture this: There’s a data presentation format you’ve wa
 nted to try for ages. Now\, all of a sudden\, you’ve got a perfect story
  to use it on — but it’s running in two days.\nYour current systems ca
 n’t make it happen. Third-party solutions don’t fit your organization
 ’s look and feel. Starting from a blank code-editor window wouldn’t ge
 t it done in time. What to do?\nThis session will show how one journalist 
 solved that problem\, using agentic AI to describe an intended solution 
 — and then iterate on functionality — all while guarding against AI ha
 llucinations and other possible pitfalls.\nIt’s not a silver bullet\, an
 d it won’t absolve you of having to vet logic and think critically. But 
 when done right\, it can be a massive force multiplier for someone who has
  the technical knowledge (but needs to meet a tight deadline).\nFolks with
  some coding knowledge will get the most out of this session. Laptops will
  be provided.\n\nAI | Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:204
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1168
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Data collection at scale for countries where data is hidde
 n
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T090000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T100000
UID:nicar-2026-1170@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Learn about collecting data for countries where data is diffic
 ult to obtain\, hidden\, or behind wonky websites that don’t give you ac
 cess to actual insights. Find out how to obtain data and support reporting
  pipelines - also how to gather data that’s more qualitative to suppleme
 nt the numbers.\n\nInternational\, Data analysis | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River G
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1170
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Uncovering wrongdoing with AI: Real-world methods and ethi
 cal boundaries
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T170000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T180000
UID:nicar-2026-1174@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:In this panel\, journalists who have deployed AI on cross-bord
 er investigations share practical techniques\, limits and guardrails for u
 sing LLMs and machine learning in data reporting.\nCase studies include: s
 craping court records and classifying gender-based violence cases in Eswat
 ini using GPT-assisted workflows\; using a hybrid of OCR\, regular express
 ions and LLMs to classify and review tens of thousands of environmental im
 pact documents in France\; and using machine-learning tools to detect defo
 restation and forest fraud across Southeast Asia by building on existing s
 cientific research.\nSharing reproducible workflows\, panellists will show
  how to combine human judgment and feedback with machine assistance for do
 cument processing\, pattern detection\, classification and verification. T
 he discussion will focus on human-in-the-loop systems\, responsible disclo
 sure of AI-assisted work and strategies for managing large document sets w
 ithout compromising editorial credibility and scepticism.\nAttendees will 
 leave with concrete methods for turning messy\, unstructured data into sea
 rchable investigative resources\, practical verification checklists and gu
 idance on how to document and explain AI-assisted reporting to editors and
  audiences.\n\nInternational | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River G
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1174
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Advanced visualization and design in Datawrapper
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T154500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T164500
UID:nicar-2026-1177@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Take your Datawrapper skills to the next level. This session w
 ill cover advanced features and techniques to make your visualizations mor
 e powerful\, polished and interactive. Learn how to customize design theme
 s and use advanced chart types to communicate complex data clearly and cre
 atively.\nSome basic HTML knowledge is preferred\, but not necessary. Lapt
 ops will be provided.\n\nData viz | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:203
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1177
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Becoming acquainted with your city as a data reporter with
  no beat
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T101500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T111500
UID:nicar-2026-1182@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Early-career\, local data journalists might find themselves ne
 eding to quickly navigate the data ecosystem of a new place for the first 
 time. In this session\, panelists will share their tips and tricks for:\n-
  Learning what kinds of data are easily available in your new home\n- Buil
 ding out a "beat" for yourself\n- Collaborating across multiple desks\n- w
 orking with a wide array of datasets\n\nBeat reporting | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River D
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1182
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] The winding paths of a data journalist
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T101500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T111500
UID:nicar-2026-1184@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Data journalists have unique skills and experiences that are a
 pplicable to product design and management roles. Learn from panelists who
  have navigated unexpected journeys to find their niche in the data world.
  This panel is great for people who are curious about making a career shif
 t\, and hearing from professionals who have firsthand experience in making
  these transitions. Our panelists will share their strategies and lessons 
 learned\, offering valuable insights for those considering a similar caree
 r pivot.\n\nCareer\, Management | Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:102
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1184
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Demo] Five demos for finding things with A.I. outside of chatbots
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T090000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T100000
UID:nicar-2026-1187@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:The most exciting new A.I. tools don't involve chatbots. We al
 l have big documents and datasets. Sometimes we think we know approximatel
 y what's inside — but we just need to find it. In this session\, we'll s
 how you five more technical ways that A.I. can be used to supercharge the 
 investigative process. We will demo semantic search for text\, spreadsheet
 s and images\; embedding and clustering\; and identifying visual objects i
 n media — all in tools you can use yourself to solve real journalistic p
 roblems\, without having to endure ChatGPT's excessive use of em-dashes an
 d its other limitations.\n\nAI | Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:White River G
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1187
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Introducing libfec\, a faster FEC filing parser
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T113000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T123000
UID:nicar-2026-1190@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:A new election cycle means a brand new open source tool for pa
 rsing the Federal Election Commission's custom .fec file format! This year
  `libfec` has been released\, a new toolkit that parses FEC files even fas
 ter than pre-existing tools\, and uses the FEC's API to find the filings f
 or the exact candidate\, election\, or PAC that you care about.\nThis clas
 s will go over how to use libfec in a midterm election year — finding al
 l individual donors for all candidates in a House or Senate race\, seeing 
 where campaigns spend their money\, and tracking down Super PACs that fuel
  outside spending in a newsroom's district. Along the way participants wil
 l learn how to use libfec to source all this data\, including how to expor
 t data into CSV\, SQLite\, or JSON for further analysis or data visualizat
 ions.\nParticipants should have a basic knowledge of using the command lin
 e. Laptops will be provided.\n\nData analysis\, Tools & Tech | Skill: Inte
 rmediate
LOCATION:205
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1190
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Data journalism for new reporters
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T090000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T100000
UID:nicar-2026-1193@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:"If you build it - they will come":  Many local reporters migh
 t not have the time and/or knowledge to incorporate data skills to their w
 ork. So how do you get into thinking and then doing data journalism? This 
 session will include examples and ideas on where to start and how to work 
 to raise awareness about data and how to use it.\nOver the next few days\,
  you'll see there is a seemingly endless number of things you can learn in
  the data journalism world. It can be daunting! But everyone at this confe
 rence started at the same place as you. We'll help you get started! This s
 ession will cover the basics of data journalism\, starting with what it is
 \, tips for building up your skills and advice for how you can — realist
 ically — integrate these skills into your daily reporting.\n\nLocal | Sk
 ill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River G
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1193
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Demo] Covering growing corporate power\, even on deadline
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T113000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T123000
UID:nicar-2026-1194@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:As corporate influence and power grows\, it grows increasingly
  important to document the broader impact of business leaders' actions. Fo
 r instance\, companies are fined billions of dollars each year for stealin
 g workers' wages\, degrading the environment\, defrauding the government\,
  cheating consumers\, and other misconduct - using Violation Tracker\, rep
 orters can look up the behavior of companies across more than 450 federal\
 , state\, and local regulatory agencies. Many of those same companies also
  receive billions in taxpayer subsidies in the name of economic developmen
 t - using Subsidy Tracker\, reporters can explore those tax breaks and oth
 er giveaways. Taken together\, these two databases can help a reporter fin
 d patterns and trends in the ways businesses operate\, and explore the way
 s governments enable poor behavior by corporate leaders to continue.\n\nSt
 ory ideas | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River D
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1194
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Special] To whom it may concern: An honest conversation with data
  team hiring managers
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T154500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T164500
UID:nicar-2026-1198@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:It’s hard to know what to expect when interviewing for data 
 journalism jobs. What are hiring managers looking for in your resume and c
 over letter? Are you expected to have a personal website\, Github or socia
 l media presence? What should you come prepared to talk about during each 
 stage of the interview process? Join us for a panel discussion on how diff
 erent news organizations approach hiring. Be sure to bring your questions 
 for the Q&A segment.\nPlease note that this session will not be recorded.\
 n\nCareer | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River D
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1198
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
