BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Following the money in college sports’ new era
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T090000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T100000
UID:nicar-2026-1286@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:College sports have changed faster in the past five years than
  in the previous five decades. Join us as we break down the changes in col
 lege athletics and look at what’s coming\, all of which makes accurate d
 ata critical\, especially financial data. We’ll walk through the college
  finance data\, explain new categories available and how to use them (and 
 how not to). We’ll also discuss how journalists can secure information a
 bout athlete name\, image\, and likeness deals obtained via Freedom of Inf
 ormation requests. Panelists will also explore current and emerging financ
 ial trends in the industry\, highlighting issues that journalists across t
 he country should be monitoring\, including the $1B in severance paid to g
 et coaches NOT to coach. We'll cover rising student fees\, challenges to e
 quity\, and new athlete revenue-sharing payments. The panelists will also 
 discuss other stories of interest in the future of college sports\, includ
 ing the prospect of Congressional intervention and the possibility that co
 llege athletes become employees.\nThis panel is especially suitable for co
 llege students or anyone looking for college sports data and trying to nav
 igate the new rules.\n\nBeat reporting\, Sports\, Story ideas | Skill: Beg
 inner
LOCATION:White River B
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1286
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Find public records and leaks: The new OCCRP Aleph Pro
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T090000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T100000
UID:nicar-2026-1287@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:You’ve got a leak\, a name\, or a suspicious company — wha
 t’s your next move? In a world of complex financial secrecy\, uncovering
  the truth demands data power. Join this hands-on workshop to master the a
 ll-new OCCRP Aleph Pro\, holding over four billion records of leaks\, sanc
 tions\, corporate registries\, and beyond. For years\, Aleph has been the 
 backbone of hundreds of investigations\, and we have now evolved it to mee
 t the challenges of modern reporting. Bring your laptop and learn to cross
 -reference targets\, generate structured entities from raw text\, and map 
 hidden connections into visual networks. You will also learn how to secure
  access to protected leaks curated for journalists\, activists\, and resea
 rchers. It's time to power your next investigation using Aleph Pro.\nPleas
 e\nfill out this form\nby Wednesday\, March 4th\, to have an account creat
 ed and access granted for OCCRP Aleph Pro. Because this will be a highly i
 nteractive session where you'll have the opportunity to create your own in
 vestigations and visual networks using Aleph Pro\, prior account setup is 
 strictly required.\nThis session is good for beginners and anyone who want
 s to learn to use Aleph Pro.\n\nInternational | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:201
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1287
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Behind the stories: 2025 Philip Meyer Winners
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T154500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T164500
UID:nicar-2026-1288@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:A data deep dive into the 2025 Philip Meyer Award winners. Hea
 r from reporters on how they gathered\, cleaned\, analyzed and visualized 
 the data behind some of the year's biggest stories.\n\nStory ideas | Skill
 : Beginner
LOCATION:White River I
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1288
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Finding the story: Using DNS search for investigative j
 ournalism
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T154500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T164500
UID:nicar-2026-1289@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Every online interaction begins with a lookup in the Domain Na
 me System (DNS)\, the backbone of the Internet. As a result\, there are di
 gital footprints left behind in the DNS. With the demise of Whois\, invest
 igative reporters are looking for new tools to uncover these footprints. L
 earn how to use DNSDB Scout\, a tool to query DNSDB\, a historical passive
  DNS database\, to discover previously unknown online connections and gain
  new information to advance your  ongoing and breaking news investigations
 .\nBasic knowledge of the Domain Name System (DNS) is helpful\, but not re
 quired. Attendees will need to bring their own laptop (no tablets) to part
 icipate in this class.\n\nData analysis\, Story ideas | Skill: Intermediat
 e
LOCATION:201
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1289
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Deep dive: Navigating nonprofit data
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T101500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T123000
UID:nicar-2026-1290@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:More than half a million organizations — from your local hum
 ane society to some of the largest hospital chains in the nation — file 
 annual public tax returns detailing revenue\, expenses\, staffing informat
 ion\, and more. In this hands-on session\, we’ll use spreadsheets to dig
  into filing data and answer questions about nonprofit organizations that 
 you can apply to nearly any beat or coverage area. No coding experience is
  necessary\, but we’ll discuss ways to dig further into these datasets u
 sing code.\nYou must bring your own laptop (no tablets) to participate.\n\
 nBeat reporting\, Public records | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:209
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1290
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
