BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] AI tools for journalists
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T090000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T111500
UID:nicar-2026-1302@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:In this session\, Mike Reilley of JournalistsToolbox.ai will s
 how you the latest and greatest AI and other free software tools for data 
 journalists. We'll work with datasets and use AI tools to analyze and visu
 alize them. We'll explore weaknesses\, flaws and ethical issues with tools
 . We'll also work with a few multimedia tools as well. This session is goo
 d for beginners. Attendees will need to bring their own laptop (no tablets
 ) to participate in this class.\n\nTools & Tech\, AI | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:201
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1302
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] First PMTiles Map: How to map massive datasets
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T101500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T111500
UID:nicar-2026-1303@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Join Ben Welsh and Jon Schleuss to learn how to display a mass
 ive dataset on an interactive map using PMTiles and MapLibre.\nThis one-ho
 ur\, hands-on class will show you how to:\nConvert massive shapefiles to t
 he compact\nPMTiles\nformat using\ntippecanoe\nDisplay the tiles on an int
 eractive map using\nMapLibre GL JS\nCreate a data-driven style that colors
  features based on their attributes\n\nMapping\, Data viz | Skill: Interme
 diate
LOCATION:104
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1303
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Monitoring police accountability laws across the U.S.
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T170000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T180000
UID:nicar-2026-1304@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Led by California and New York\, states across the U.S. have b
 egun adopting laws to give the public access to police accountability data
 \, including use-of-force and discipline records. But what’s available v
 aries by state\, and there are no central repositories for tracking proble
 m police officers (and some agencies fail to access what is available). In
  addition\, laws that are intended to make sure problem police never work 
 in law enforcement again are riddled with inconsistent application.\nThis 
 panel will take a deeper look at the documents and data across the country
 \, and the stories reporters have done in multiple states to illuminate wh
 at has previously been shielded from the public. We dig into how we went a
 bout forming news/university/private partnerships to report on unevenly en
 forced police discipline\, and how you could execute a similar project wit
 h the data and documents in your state.\nThis panel was planned in conjunc
 tion with "Utilizing new police misconduct and employment databases\," sch
 eduled for Friday at 9:00 a.m. This panel will focus on changing laws\, da
 ta partnerships and developing stories\; the next panel will give specific
  how-tos using available data.\n\nBeat reporting\, Story ideas | Skill: Be
 ginner
LOCATION:White River B
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1304
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Excel 1: Getting started with spreadsheets (PC lab)
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T090000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T100000
UID:nicar-2026-1306@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:In this introduction to spreadsheets\, you'll begin analyzing 
 data with Excel\, a simple but powerful tool. You'll learn how to enter da
 ta\, navigate spreadsheets and conduct simple calculations like sum\, aver
 age and median.\nThis class will be taught on PC computers.\nThis session 
 is good for: Data beginners. Laptops will be provided.\n\nData analysis | 
 Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:203
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1306
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Excel 2: Formulas & sorting (PC lab)
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T101500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T111500
UID:nicar-2026-1307@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Much of Excel's power comes in the form of formulas. In this c
 lass\, you'll learn how to use them to analyze data with the eye of a jour
 nalist. Yes\, math will be involved\, but it's totally worth it! This clas
 s will show you how calculations like change\, percent change\, rates and 
 ratios can beef up your reporting.\nThis class will be taught on PC comput
 ers.\nThis session is good for: Anyone who is comfortable navigating Excel
 . Laptops will be provided.\n\nData analysis | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:203
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1307
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Excel 3: Filtering & pivot tables (PC lab)
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T113000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T123000
UID:nicar-2026-1308@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:A look at the awesome power of pivot — and how to use it to 
 analyze your dataset in minutes rather than hours. We'll work up to using 
 a pivot table by first sorting and filtering a dataset\, learning how to f
 ind story ideas along the way.\nThis class will be taught on PC computers.
 \nThis session is good for: Anyone familiar with formulas\, sorting and fi
 ltering in Excel or another spreadsheet program. Laptops will be provided.
 \n\nData analysis | Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:203
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1308
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Finding the story: Using DNS search for investigative j
 ournalism (repeat)
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T113000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T123000
UID:nicar-2026-1309@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Every online interaction begins with a lookup in the Domain Na
 me System (DNS)\, the backbone of the Internet. As a result\, there are di
 gital footprints left behind in the DNS. With the demise of Whois\, invest
 igative reporters are looking for new tools to uncover these footprints. L
 earn how to use DNSDB Scout\, a tool to query DNSDB\, a historical passive
  DNS database\, to discover previously unknown online connections and gain
  new information to advance your  ongoing and breaking news investigations
 .\nBasic knowledge of the Domain Name System (DNS) is helpful\, but not re
 quired. Attendees will need to bring their own laptop (no tablets) to part
 icipate in this class.\n\nData analysis\, Story ideas | Skill: Intermediat
 e
LOCATION:202
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1309
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] PyCAR
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T090000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T180000
UID:nicar-2026-1310@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:This hands-on workshop will teach journalists basic programmin
 g concepts using the Python programming language. The class will introduce
  language basics and useful libraries in the course of a typical reporting
  project: scraping data from the web\, analyzing a spreadsheet and visuali
 zing the results.\nThis session is good for beginners who want to get star
 ted with Python. Preregistration is required and seating is limited. You m
 ust bring your own laptop (no tablets) to this training.\n\nData analysis 
 | Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:209
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1310
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
