BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Using CAPTCHA-solving services to automate difficult we
 b-scraping projects
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T143000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T153000
UID:nicar-2026-1320@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:This class will teach attendees how to use CAPTCHA-solving ser
 vices to automate CAPTCHA solutions in web scraping. Attendees will learn 
 how to efficiently identify and send required elements to the CAPTCHA-solv
 ing service and apply the unique codes received to navigate past CAPTCHAs 
 encountered during web scraping. Special focus will be placed on tackling 
 Google's reCAPTCHA v2\, a commonly used CAPTCHA on the web\, alongside str
 ategies for overcoming challenges presented by more complex websites. The 
 class will provide practical skills in CAPTCHA solving\, equipping attende
 es with the knowledge to implement these solutions in their projects.\nThi
 s session is good for journalists with some Python experience. Attendees w
 ill need to bring their own laptop (no tablets) to participate in this cla
 ss.\n\nTools & Tech | Skill: Advanced
LOCATION:209
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1320
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Spatial analysis in R: 101
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T143000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T153000
UID:nicar-2026-1321@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Learn how to use spatial functions in R to level up your repor
 ting. We’ll explore tools for mapping\, spatial joins\, buffering and ca
 lculating distance — all using a single package. We’ll center a story 
 published by The Baltimore Banner on gun violence around schools to showca
 se an application of these functions and demonstrate best practices for ba
 sic geospatial analysis.\nThis session is good for beginner and intermedia
 te journalists with some familiarity with R.\nLaptops will be provided.\n\
 nMapping\, Data analysis\, Tools & Tech | Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:203
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1321
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Spatial analysis in R: 201
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T154500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T164500
UID:nicar-2026-1322@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Take your spatial skills up a notch by learning to use image-b
 ased data derived from satellite observations. In this session\, you’ll 
 discover how to navigate tricky filetypes like netCDF and TIF\, all within
  the comfort of RStudio. Learn how to extract decades of real-time measure
 ments from variables like ocean heat\, temperature\, land use\, air pollut
 ion and more. By the end\, you’ll have the tools to join satellite measu
 rements with traditional shapefiles.\nThis session is good for journalists
  who are comfortable with the basics of R and Rstudio. Attending "Spatial 
 analysis in R: 101" is recommended. Laptops will be provided.\n\nMapping\,
  Data analysis\, Tools & Tech | Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:203
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1322
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Spatial analysis in R: 301
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T170000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T180000
UID:nicar-2026-1323@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Data that lacks a shared column for direct joins can often sti
 ll be connected through maps. But common geographies like census tracts an
 d precincts rarely align perfectly. Despite these challenges\, it’s stil
 l possible to estimate how votes shifted across neighborhoods or calculate
  statistical relationships using Census data. This process is called inter
 polation — learn how to translate data from one map to another and bridg
 e geographic gaps in their data analysis. This session is good for journal
 ists who are comfortable with the basics of R and Rstudio. Attending "Spat
 ial analysis in R: 201" is recommended. Laptops will be provided.\n\nMappi
 ng\, Data analysis\, Tools & Tech | Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:203
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1323
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Demo] Big Local News tools\, wares and resources
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T101500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T111500
UID:nicar-2026-1324@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:A lightning-round showcase of innovative newsroom tools and ot
 her resources that can help you collaborate on data journalism projects\, 
 harvest data and documents at scale\, and track institutions for accountab
 ility reporting\, from police agencies to state legislatures.\n\nTools & T
 ech | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River B
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1324
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Supporting the next generation of journalists through a hi
 storic slide in U.S. press freedom
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T143000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T153000
UID:nicar-2026-1325@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:As the next generation of journalists enters the field at a ti
 me when the Committee to Protect Journalists has warned that “press free
 dom in the United States is under siege\,” we explore how student report
 ers are navigating that threatening climate on and off campus. We hear fro
 m student journalists whose universities have encroached on editorial inde
 pendence or withdrawn institutional support. We also hear from a student j
 ournalist who was arrested and convicted for doing his job. As the industr
 y reckons with this reality on a broad scale\, we speak with a senior repo
 rter at the U.S. Press Freedom Tracker and invite all in attendance to joi
 n us in a conversation as we ask: How can we best support our student coll
 eagues under such conditions?\n\nStudents\, Story ideas\, Career | Skill: 
 Beginner
LOCATION:White River B
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1325
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Accessing records to report on immigration enforcement act
 ions
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T101500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T111500
UID:nicar-2026-1326@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Data sets and public records offer critical context for covera
 ge of immigration enforcement actions taking place in communities across t
 he country\, but it’s often difficult to know where to look for this inf
 ormation or how to respond when access is denied. This session will provid
 e practical tips for journalists on how to obtain data and records for rep
 orting on immigration issues\, and the resources available to push for gre
 ater transparency when necessary.\n\nData analysis\, Story ideas | Skill: 
 Intermediate
LOCATION:White River I
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1326
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] A view from both sides: 5 practical strategies for success
 ful public records requests
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T170000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T180000
UID:nicar-2026-1327@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Employing a smart strategy from the outset can make all the di
 fference between progress and pushback when it comes to accessing public r
 ecords. This session offers insights from both the PIO and journalist pers
 pectives to help you shape your requests to be as successful as possible a
 nd know where to turn when facing delays or denials.\n\nPublic records | S
 kill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River B
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1327
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] Building blocks of a better team
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T170000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T180000
UID:nicar-2026-1328@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Is your team clicking together like a perfectly built structur
 e or clunking along like mismatched pieces? Strong collaboration and commu
 nication are the foundation of any high-performing team\, and in this inte
 ractive session\, you’ll discover how to strengthen both through the pow
 er of play.\nUsing building blocks as both metaphor and hands-on tool\, we
 ’ll explore what it takes to build trust\, align around shared goals and
  adapt to change. You’ll gain fresh insights into team dynamics\, leader
 ship styles and the invisible structures that support effective teamwork. 
 Come ready to build\, reflect and leave with practical strategies for asse
 mbling a more connected\, resilient team: one brick at a time.\n\nEvent | 
 Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River I
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1328
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] ezesri: Mining public mapping data from Esri services
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T154500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T164500
UID:nicar-2026-1329@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Local governments often publish spatial data to mapping giant 
 Esri’s platforms before posting it anywhere else. Learn how to use ezesr
 i to discover more than 100\,000 public data sets and extract them without
  code in journalist-friendly formats (csv\, geoJSON\, shapefile). The tool
  also features a Python package for power users. Some data experience will
  be useful for this session. Attendees will need to bring their own laptop
  (no tablets) to participate in this class.\n\nMapping | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:201
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1329
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] We're managers\, ask us anything: career\, networking\, me
 ntorship
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T170000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T180000
UID:nicar-2026-1330@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Name just about any kind of newroom\, job\, story or industry 
 crisis and these powerhouse journalists have been there\, done it and surv
 ived - stronger and better than ever! They'll share all their best tips fo
 r working through tough times and making it as a journalist\, finding and 
 telling the best stories\, how to make your IRE membership work for you an
 d more. We'll save lots of time at the end for questions and some lively n
 etworking before the opening reception.\n\nCareer | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River E
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1330
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] From vibes to scores: Build your own AI benchmark
DTSTART;TZID=EDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260308T090000
DTEND;TZID=EDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260308T123000
UID:nicar-2026-1332@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:You've built some sort of AI workflow - maybe a copy editor\, 
 idea generator\, automated podcast\, research assistant or tip pipeline - 
 but how do you know how well it really works? And how do you know when it 
 stops working?\nIn this session participants will learn how to define "goo
 d enough" for an AI use case\, implement both code-based and LLM-as-judge 
 scorers\, build a small test representative test set\, and run evaluations
 .\nWe'll be using Pydantic AI (Python) with the Braintrust platform\, but 
 concepts are perfectly portable to no-code tools or other evaluation toolk
 its.\nParticipants should have a basic understanding of Python and have at
  least basic experience with AI use cases.\n\nAI | Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:104
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1332
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Implementing accessibility
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T113000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T123000
UID:nicar-2026-1333@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:You've got the hang of why you should be doing basic accessibi
 lity\, but do you know what to do when it's time to put it into practice? 
 In this interactive\, hands-on session\, we'll teach you how to write alt 
 text\, then challenge you with photos\, infographics and maps right in the
  session.\nWhether or not you've attended the panel\, Accessibility Basics
 \, this session will be fun and educational. Attendees will need to bring 
 their own laptop (no tablets) to participate in this class.\n\nEquity\, in
 clusion and accessibility | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:201
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1333
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Demo] The SLAPP Back Initiative: Building a first-of-its-kind dat
 abase
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T101500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T111500
UID:nicar-2026-1334@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:The SLAPP Back Initiative: Building a first-of-its-kind databa
 se\nHave you considered building a database of your own but are not sure w
 here to start? Join lead researcher Susanna Granieri of The SLAPP Back Ini
 tiative\, a first-of-its-kind database tracking strategic lawsuits against
  public participation\, meritless and frivolous actions used to chill spee
 ch and deter scrutiny. In this demo session\, Susanna will outline the tea
 m's steps from inception to launch: What research tools were used? How was
  the methodology developed? How did they interrogate the data and bulletpr
 oof their findings? What questions have they answered\, and what questions
  remain? She'll also show you how\, as the database grows\, it can help em
 power your journalism\, identifying common offenders and frequent targets 
 in your state.\n\nResearch | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River B
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1334
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
