BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Special] ICE enforcement violence needs a collaborative database!
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T154500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T164500
UID:nicar-2026-1337@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Several newsrooms are collecting and reporting on instances of
  immigration enforcement violence. The Trace\, The Marshall Project and Th
 e New York Times and others have at different points this year chronicled 
 the violence of federal immigration agents across the U.S. But this moment
  calls for a comprehensive and collective effort -- not a competitive one.
  Join brains to plan and execute a national reporting database that will c
 atalog as many instances of immigration enforcement violence as possible. 
 Together we'll develop a plan\, roles\, and tooling to begin broad collabo
 rative tracking of immigration agent violence. We'll name the project and 
 draft a pitch document for news nerds to bring back to their senior manage
 rs for official organization-level adoption and sponsoring. Past projects 
 like this have done nothing short of shape history -- COVID Tracking Proje
 ct\, anybody?? Come help make the most of these painful times.\n\nBeat rep
 orting\, Story ideas | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River B
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1337
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Finding the story: Using data to report on statehouses
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T090000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T100000
UID:nicar-2026-1339@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Whenever journalists are told to follow the money\, we know th
 at always means having a strong grasp on the data that is used to advocate
  for bills and the backdrop of who may be funding what. Come learn how to 
 dig into the data out there with some hands-on exercises. Laptops will be 
 provided.\n\nStory ideas | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:209
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1339
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Panel] What your newsroom knows (but can’t find)
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T170000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260305T180000
UID:nicar-2026-1340@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Newsroom archives hold decades of reporting. They represent th
 ousands of sources\, events and institutional knowledge built over the yea
 rs. And yet they’re incredibly unwieldy and difficult to leverage. How m
 any of you search your own newsroom’s archives through Google? In this p
 anel\, we'll walk you through how we built Subline\, an end-to-end system 
 that extracts knowledge graphs from newsroom archives. We’ll demonstrate
  how it supports smarter archive search\, article link prediction\, multi-
 step investigative queries\, and better reader-facing recommendations.\n\n
 Tools & Tech\, Story ideas | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:White River D
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1340
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Demo] Automating your data collection with dashboards and AI spon
 sored by Bright Data
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T113000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260306T123000
UID:nicar-2026-1341@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:With AI taking on a role in nearly everyone’s lives\, whethe
 r it’s simple interactions through platforms they already use or fully b
 uilt systems\, it’s time for you to level up your data collection practi
 ces with AI as well. In this session\, we’ll review traditional data col
 lection and explore automation to create dashboards that let your readers 
 and viewers explore topics.\n\nAI | Skill: Intermediate
LOCATION:White River E
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1341
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] Cracking the code: How to read local government budgets
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T143000
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T153000
UID:nicar-2026-1343@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Local government budgets are plans — Hopes. Dreams. Needs. P
 riorities. They reflect power. They make promises. In this session\, you
 ’ll learn how to read them and how to find the enterprise stories in the
  numbers. I’ll also share takeaways from public finance professionals\, 
 including how they navigate the politics in the budgeting process. Lessons
  in this session apply to all local council\, commission\, school and auth
 ority budgets.\nThis session is good for all levels of experience! Attende
 es will need to bring their own laptops (preferably no tablets) for the tr
 aining.\n\nData analysis\, Public records | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:201
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1343
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] From spreadsheet to map in 60 minutes
DTSTART;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T101500
DTEND;TZID=EST;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260307T111500
UID:nicar-2026-1344@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:Have a spreadsheet with latitude and longitude coordinates and
  need to turn it into a map quickly? This hands-on QGIS session focuses on
  the practical workflow journalists use most: importing tabular data\, cre
 ating a point layer\, adding geographic context\, and styling a clear them
 atic map ready for publication. We’ll skip the broad GIS overview and di
 ve straight into the essential steps so you leave with a publishable map a
 nd a repeatable workflow you can use in your reporting.\n\nMapping | Skill
 : Intermediate
LOCATION:203
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1344
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:[Hands-on] NICAR-L hackathon 🤠
DTSTART;TZID=EDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260308T090000
DTEND;TZID=EDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260308T100000
UID:nicar-2026-1346@ire.org
DESCRIPTION:The NICAR-L listserv has long been a source of inspiration and
  knowledge-sharing for data journalists around the world. But tapping into
  the decades of wisdom contained in its archives is difficult with existin
 g tools. Let's build something better!\nThis session is good for people wh
 o get excited about cleaning dirty\, inconsistently formatted data to powe
 r user-friendly tools. Attendees will need to bring their own laptop (no t
 ablets) to participate in this class.\n\nEvent | Skill: Beginner
LOCATION:202
URL:https://schedules.ire.org/nicar-2026#session-1346
X-SOURCE:NICAR 2026
